title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:link
type="local"
href="nst-002J.xml"
addr="nst-002J"
title="Proof by contradiction">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>. Assume for contradiction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is not uniformly continuous. Then there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex> such that for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta >0]]></fr:tex> and for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a,b\in  X]]></fr:tex> we have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[d(a,b)<\delta \quad \hbox {and}\quad \rho (f(a),f(b))\geq \varepsilon .]]></fr:tex>
Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is compact, it is <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0022.xml"
addr="ca-0022"
title="Sequentially compact subset">sequentially compact</fr:link> by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0023.xml"
addr="ca-0023"
title="Characterization of compactness for metric spaces">Characterization of compactness for metric spaces</fr:link>. Then for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, there exists <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y_{n}\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[d(x_{n},y_{n})<\frac {1}{n}\quad \hbox {and}\quad \rho (f(x_{n}),f(y_{n}))\geq \varepsilon .]]></fr:tex>
But by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0022.xml"
addr="ca-0022"
title="Sequentially compact subset">sequential compactness</fr:link> there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> and a subsequence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n_{k}})]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n_{k}}\to  x]]></fr:tex> converges. Then using the triangle inequality, we have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align} d(y_{n_{k}},x) & \leq  d(y_{n_{k}},x_{n_{k}}) + d(x_{n_{k}},x)\\ &\leq \frac {1}{n_{k}}  + d(x_{n_{k}},x), \end {align}]]></fr:tex>
which goes to zero for sufficiently large <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{k}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(y_{n_{k}})\to  x]]></fr:tex>. Then by continuity of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, their images (using the triangle inequality):
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x_{n_{k}}), f(y_{n_{k}}))\leq \rho (f(x_{n_{k}}), f(x)) + \rho (f(x), f(y_{n_{k}})),]]></fr:tex>
which goes to zero by continuity. But this contradicts <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x_{n_{k}}),f(x))\geq \varepsilon ]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> must be uniformly continuous.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
